question_text: How does paragraph 1 introduce the ideas that ravens may perceive time and plan for the future?
options: It mentions a poem that considers whether a raven can see the future and then discusses why people have traditionally doubted that ravens have the ability to plan.
It references a poem about a raven that seems to have insight into the future and then mentions new information that suggests ravens have the ability to plan.
It mentions a poem that led people to believe that ravens are aware of the future and then explains why scientists want to study ravens’ ability to plan.
It references a poem about a raven that predicts the future and then describes the importance of differentiating ravens’ instincts from their ability to plan.

question_text:
Read these sentences from paragraph 2.

For example, many animals hoard food so that they will not run out later, but scientists who study animals would not call hoarding a decision to plan for the future. This action is merely instinctual.

Which statement describes the effect of the phrase “merely instinctual” in the passage?
options: It implies that animals are skilled at finding and saving food for later consumption.
It conveys that many animals will usually prioritize gathering food over other activities.
It suggests that animals often store more food than they will be able to consume
It emphasizes that many animals collect food automatically rather than with true intention.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 1.

 At Lund University in Sweden, researchers argue that ravens may be able to think ahead and even plan for the future.

Which sentence from paragraph 4 provides support for this argument?
options: “Once the ravens learned the behavior, the researchers presented the birds with four stones.”
“A researcher would trade the ravens a large treat for a bottle cap.”
“Later, the researchers presented the ravens with a group of items, including small treats and the bottle cap.”
“The ravens chose the bottle cap over the treats and waited for the original researcher to trade with them again so that they could get more treats.”

question_text: In the first experiment described in paragraph 4, which of the ravens’ behaviors provides the strongest evidence for the claim that the birds are capable of planning?
options: They accepted treats from the unlocked box.
They set aside the stones that would unlock the box.
They learned which stone could open the box.
They waited for researchers to bring the box.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 4.

In both experiments, the ravens waited patiently for up to seventeen hours for the researcher to return.

 How does this sentence fit into the overall structure of the passage and contribute to the development of ideas?
options: It concludes the description of the experiments, supporting the idea that ravens can make decisions for the future.
It establishes the timeline required in experiments designed to determine learned behaviors in ravens.
It reveals how the ravens solved the problems posed in the experiments, proving that ravens have the ability to plan ahead.
It indicates that hoarding food is both an instinctual and a learned behavior among ravens.

question_text: With which statement would the author of the passage most likely agree?
options: Scientists are unlikely to be able to conduct an experiment that can genuinely distinguish between instinctual and learned behaviors in animals.
Scientists should continue researching to find more evidence to support the idea that some animals show signs of advanced intelligence.
Scientists should be careful about making conclusions about animal intelligence based on experiments that rely on training animals.
Scientists can confirm data on whether animals have the ability to plan by performing experiments on additional species known for their intelligence.

question_text: How does paragraph 5 fit into the overall structure of the passage and contribute to the development of ideas?
options: It introduces a problem with the results of the study at Lund University, suggesting that some scientists believe that further research will not lead to a clear answer.
It summarizes the final steps of the study at Lund University, emphasizing the difficulties researchers had in differentiating between true planning and practiced actions.
It provides a conclusion to the information about the Lund University study, indicating that some scientists think further research is needed in order to prove the idea.
It lists the effects of the study at Lund University, implying that researchers should have designed experiments that better differentiated between planning and instinct.

question_text: The author conveys a point of view on the study of animal intelligence mainly by

comparing the results of different experiments that were designed to test animal intelligence.

Read these lines from the poem.

I can already see how this will end. (line 1)

How Brooklyn makes me nostalgic

question_text: Which sentence from the excerpt best explains why Wade reserved Peroxide Jim for “emergency work” (paragraph 1)?
options: “Along with the wagon had come the fresh horses—one of them being Peroxide Jim, a supple, powerful, clean-limbed buckskin, a horse, I think, that had as fine and intelligent an animal-face as any creature I ever saw. ” (paragraph 1)

“Before him, behind him, beside him, pressing hard upon his horse, galloped the frenzied steers, and beyond them a multitude borne on, and bearing him on, by the heave of the galloping herd.” (paragraph 10)

“He knew that he was being borne toward the rim, how fast he could not tell, but he knew by the swish of the brush against his tapaderos and the plunging of the horse that the ground was growing stonier, that they were nearing the rocks.” (paragraph 11)

“From the flash of the lightning the horse had taken the bit, had covered an indescribably perilous path at top speed, had outrun the herd and turned it from the edge of the rim rock, without a false step or a tremor of fear.” (paragraph 16)

“It was not to soothe their savage breasts that the riders sang to the cattle, but rather to preempt the dreaded silence, to relieve the tension, and so to prevent the shock of any sudden startling noise.” (paragraph 5)

“So they sang and rode and the night wore on to one o’clock, when Wade, coming up on the rimrock side, felt a cool breeze fan his face, and caught a breath of fresh, moist wind with the taste of water in it.” (paragraph 6)
“Then the breeze caught the dust and carried it back from the gray-coated, ghostly shapes, and Wade saw that the animals were still moving in a circle.” (paragraph 9)

options: It hints at the change in the setting that caused Wade to suddenly become alert
It creates a false sense of calm that shows how unprepared the men were for what was about to happen.
It indicates that Wade was a skillful leader in unpredictable circumstances.
It presents the incident that caused the main conflict Wade and Peroxide Jim addressed.

question_text:
Read these sentences from the excerpt.

He was riding to turn the herd, too, back from the rim, as the horse also knew. (paragraph 11)

How do these sentences develop a central idea in the excerpt?
options: They suggest that Wade would have been unable to save the herd without Peroxide Jim.
They imply that Wade spent many hours training Peroxide Jim to herd cattle
They show that Peroxide Jim was able to understand a situation and take action.

Read this sentence from paragraph 13.

 Close on their left bore down the flank of the herd, and on their right, under their very feet, was a precipice, so close that they felt its blackness—its three hundred feet of fall!

options: struggled to see the front of the herd.
had to ride quickly to keep up with the herd.

question_text: How do the details in paragraphs 14–16 help convey a central idea of the excerpt?
options: They highlight Peroxide Jim’s natural ability to control the herd.

question_text: Which sentence from the passage suggests that using Internet search engines may lead people to rely less on their own ability to recall information?
options: “In the past few decades, the Internet has become an integral component of daily life for many people.” (paragraph 1)
“The Internet group was required to use the search engine Google to answer eight challenging trivia questions.” (paragraph 2)
“Their results showed that 83 percent of the Internet group continued to consult Google in the second round, while only 63 percent of the memory group chose to do so.” (paragraph 2)

question_text: The details in paragraph 3 about cognitive offloading convey a central idea of the passage by
options: suggesting that reliance on the Internet for information is inevitable.
demonstrating how the methods used to store and find information have changed over time.
explaining how encyclopedias and the Internet are similar sources of information.
implying that more information can be understood now than ever before.

question_text: How do the details about the experiment described in paragraph 5 convey a central idea of the passage?
options: They suggest that the act of repeating information by typing it on a keyboard may improve a person’s memory.
They explain that a person will forget information faster if the information is considered unimportant.
They indicate that a person may start to forget details when the amount of information becomes overwhelming.
They suggest that memory is affected by whether a person expects to have access to the information in the future.

question_text: The study described in paragraph 6 influenced researchers’ ideas about memory in the digital age by
options: highlighting instances when organizing detailed information made it easier to remember.
confirming that keywords can be remembered more easily than large amounts of information.

question_text:

 As the Internet’s resources continue to expand our “external” memory, some question whether the process may cause people to depend too heavily on technology.

compare the type of information that can be obtained from the Internet with the type of information that is stored in the human brain.

passage: (1) Both Italian gelato and American ice cream are delightful treats to have on a hot summer day, but many people wonder: what is the difference between the two? (2) To start with, the butterfat content is much higher in ice cream than it is in gelato, making the Italian treat a wiser decision for people looking to make healthier choices. (3) Additionally, the mixing process, which adds less air to the frozen treat, makes gelato denser than ice cream. passage: In 1967 Katherine Switzer signed up for the Boston Marathon using her first and middle initials instead of her full NAME, AT that time, only men were permitted to officially register and receive a number for the legendary race. Switzer prevailed and finished in just over four HOURS, PAVING the way for the official rule change that allowed for the inclusion of women. In 2017, to mark the fiftieth anniversary of this pioneering event, a seventy-year-old Switzer repeated her run, wearing the number 261, THE same number she had worn in that first run in 1967.
